author: Chinua Achebe
name: Things Fall Apart
description: A powerful novel about the clash between traditional African culture and the forces of colonialism and change. Achebe's storytelling brings the life and struggles of the Igbo community vividly to life.

author: Hans Christian Andersen
name: Fairy tales
description: A collection of classic fairy tales that have delighted children and adults alike for generations. Andersen's stories are filled with imagination, whimsy, and timeless moral lessons.

author: Dante Alighieri
name: The Divine Comedy
description: An epic poem that takes the reader on a journey through Hell, Purgatory, and Heaven. Dante's masterful work explores themes of sin, redemption, and the human condition.

author: Lana
name: The Epic Of Gilgamesh
description: One of the oldest known literary works, this epic tells the story of Gilgamesh, a legendary king, and his quest for immortality. It is a profound exploration of friendship, heroism, and the meaning of life.

author: Mia Rhoades
name: The Book Of Job
description: A biblical text that addresses the nature of suffering and the justice of God. The story of Job's trials and his unwavering faith continues to inspire and challenge readers.

author: Jhonny adams
name: One Thousand and One Nights
description: A collection of Middle Eastern folktales compiled over centuries. The stories, told by Scheherazade, are rich in adventure, romance, and moral lessons.

author: Ava sins
name: Njál's Saga
description: A medieval Icelandic saga that tells the story of a long-standing blood feud. The narrative provides insight into the culture and legal system of Iceland during the Viking Age.

author: Jane Austen
name: Pride and Prejudice
description: A beloved romantic novel that critiques the British landed gentry at the end of the 18th century. The story of Elizabeth Bennet and Mr. Darcy's complicated relationship is timeless.

author: Honoré de Balzac
name: Le Père Goriot
description: A novel about the lives of the residents of a Parisian boarding house, focusing on the tragic figure of Père Goriot. Balzac's work explores themes of family, ambition, and societal change.

author: Samuel Beckett
name: Molloy, Malone Dies, The Unnamable, the trilogy
description: A trilogy of novels that explore existential themes and the human condition. Beckett's minimalist style and dark humor make these works profound and challenging.

author: Giovanni Boccaccio
name: The Decameron
description: A collection of 100 tales told by a group of young people sheltering in a secluded villa to escape the Black Death. Boccaccio's work is both a critique of society and a celebration of life and love.

author: Jorge Luis Borges
name: Ficciones
description: A collection of surreal and fantastical short stories that explore philosophical concepts and the nature of reality. Borges' work is highly influential and revered in the literary world.

author: Emily Brontë
name: Wuthering Heights
description: A haunting and passionate tale of love and revenge set on the Yorkshire moors. The complex characters and dark atmosphere make this a classic of English literature.
